# Operator-attachment readability gate (required)

When the **operator** (human user) attaches or references a file, image, screenshot, log excerpt, PDF, or other artifact that you are expected to use as evidence for analysis, debugging, or decision-making, you MUST confirm it is readable **before** relying on it. If it is not readable, you MUST stop and ask the operator for a clearer replacement. You MUST NOT silently skip or substitute your own guess.

## Why this rule exists

Unreadable attachments are a silent analysis hazard: the agent proceeds as if it saw evidence it did not, the operator assumes the attachment was consumed, and the gap is invisible until a wrong conclusion ships. The only acceptable skip is an **explicit operator decision** to proceed without that artifact — never an agent-side convenience skip.

## Scope (when this rule fires)

Fires when:

- The operator attaches one or more files or images to the conversation.
- The operator names a path and expects you to read it (`Read`, image read, log tail, PDF, CSV, etc.).
- The operator says "see the attachment", "in the screenshot", "the log I pasted", or equivalent and that artifact is load-bearing for the task.

Does NOT fire when:

- You are discovering files on your own via search/list/grep with no operator-supplied artifact in play.
- The operator already gave an explicit skip (see "Operator-only skip" below).
- The attachment is decorative or the operator states it is optional and not needed for the task.

## Required behavior

1. **Attempt to read** every operator-supplied attachment that is load-bearing for the current task (via `Read` or the appropriate tool for the media type).

2. **If readable**: proceed using the actual content. Do not summarize from memory of a prior turn unless you re-read in this turn when the attachment is still load-bearing.

3. **If not readable** (any of: tool error, permission denied, empty file, corrupt/truncated payload, illegible/blurry/low-resolution image, unreadable encoding, password-protected without password, wrong format, or content too incomplete to support the requested analysis): **STOP**. Report which attachment failed and why in one bounded line. Ask the operator for a clearer replacement (higher resolution, plain-text export, copy-paste of the relevant section, different format, unredacted version, etc.). Do **not** continue the analysis that depends on that artifact.

4. **While blocked**, you MAY still do work that does not depend on the unreadable attachment (e.g. read unrelated repo files, run commands the operator already authorized). You MUST NOT present conclusions, root-cause claims, or "done" summaries that assume content from the unreadable attachment.

5. **Final summary MUST include exactly one attachment-status line per load-bearing operator artifact**:

   - `Attachment: READ <name-or-path>`
   - `Attachment: UNREADABLE <name-or-path> — asked operator for replacement`
   - `Attachment: SKIPPED <name-or-path> (reason: operator-explicit-skip)`

   Missing lines for load-bearing attachments are a rule violation.

## Operator-only skip

The agent MUST NOT skip an unreadable attachment on its own. Skipping is allowed **only** when the operator explicitly says they cannot supply a clearer version and instructs you to proceed without it. Accept paraphrases that clearly mean the same thing, for example:

- "skip this attachment — I don't have a clearer one"
- "proceed without the screenshot"
- "ignore the log; I'll paste the error below"

When the operator skips, use reason token `operator-explicit-skip` verbatim in the summary line. Do not treat vague assent ("ok", "sure", "go ahead") as skip authorization unless it clearly refers to proceeding **without** the unreadable attachment.

## Anti-patterns (do not ship)

- Silently ignoring a failed `Read` and continuing the analysis.
- "I couldn't read the image, but based on your description…" when the attachment was load-bearing and the operator did not explicitly skip it.
- Inventing or hallucinating attachment contents to fill the gap.
- Marking a task done while a load-bearing attachment is still `UNREADABLE` and the operator has not explicitly skipped it.
- Delegating to a subagent in hopes it can "see" an attachment you could not read — the readability gate applies to the whole session; escalate to the operator instead.

## Fits the system

- **Frontier now**: always-applied guardrail in every umbraculum-toolset session; the deterministic `Attachment: READ|UNREADABLE|SKIPPED ...` summary lines make silent attachment loss visible to operator and agent.
- **Local subagents (future)**: a readonly preflight subagent can attempt bounded reads and emit the same status lines before analysis subagents run; blocked state is regex-checkable and fail-closed.
